Treatment of elderly patients
or many elderly patients, an intensive treatment with high dose cytarabine and transplantation is too toxic. here is no clear definition of elderly in this respect. rbitrarily, clinical trials often use a cutoff of 65 years or older. owever, even some patients less than 65 might be considered as elderly, in the case of cardiac disease or other comorbidity. ith a median age of 65 years at diagnosis of , half of the patients are not eligible for the β€�standardβ€� therapy with autologous transplantation. owever, even with a less intensive treatment the outcome of the fit elderly patient has improved by incorporating rituximab and maintenance therapy.
tudies investigating minimal residual disease have shown that those patients achieving a molecular complete remission after therapy have a low risk of early progression, and in general have a long event-free survival. t is therefore important to try to obtain a complete remission, also for elderly patients.30
he backbone of therapy is -. his regimen is repeated every 3 weeks, up to eight courses. he result is generally a reduction of lymphadenopathy and other symptoms. verall responses (complete and partial remissions combined) of approximately 85% can be obtained.  complete remission (), no signs of disease left on computed tomography scan and other restaging procedures, is achieved in 30%β€“40% of patients.18,31 elapse or progression is common after 2β€“3 years.18
he uropean  etwork designed a study that aimed to improve the results of induction therapy, and to prolong the duration of remission. n this randomized, multicenter study, the standard -, eight cycles, was compared with rituximab, the purine analog fludarabine, and cyclophosphamide (-), every 4 weeks, a total of six cycles. he responding patients were randomized between maintenance therapy with interferon-alpha or rituximab. his maintenance treatment was planned to continue until progression.31 n almost 7 years, 560 patients from eight countries were randomized. he median age was 70 years. he results were unexpected. he new induction regimen - did not improve the outcome; in both treatment arms the response rate (partial response and complete response) was not statistically different: after - 86%, after - 78%. he  rate was 34% and 40% respectively, also not statistically different. he  in the --treated patients was better than in the --treated patients, the survival rate after 4 years being 62% versus 47%. he toxicity of - was more severe, especially hematologic toxicity, and infections were observed more frequently.
he outcome of the maintenance treatment was very much in favor of rituximab. fter 4 years, 58% of the patients had not shown progression or relapse, compared with 29% of the patients that started interferon maintenance. his resulted in a 4-year  in the patients treated with - and rituximab maintenance of almost 85%. ight cycles of - followed by rituximab maintenance therefore now is considered the standard treatment for elderly patients with , until a new study will hopefully show further improved outcome data.
n alternative alkylating agent is bendamustine. his agent has been used for the treatment of indolent lymphomas and  in ermany for more than 20 years, but was only approved in urope and  a few years ago. n a recently randomized study in patients with indolent lymphoma or , - has been compared with -bendamustine.32 he study was designed as a noninferiority trial. he toxicity of -bendamustine was lower, except for skin rash. rythema or allergic reactions of the skin were observed in 31% of the patients, compared with 15% after -. inety-four patients in this study (18%), with a median age of 70 years, were diagnosed with a . he median  of the  patients was 35 months with -bendamustine, compared with 22 months after -. o difference in  has been observed, however.  second study, not yet published, for indolent lymphomas including , has been initiated in the . n this study, -bendamustine is being compared with - or - (rituximab with cyclophosphamide, vincristine, and prednisone).Treatment of elderly patients
For many elderly patients, an intensive treatment with high dose cytarabine and transplantation is too toxic. There is no clear definition of elderly in this respect. Arbitrarily, clinical trials often use a cutoff of 65 years or older. However, even some patients less than 65 might be considered as elderly, in the case of cardiac disease or other comorbidity. With a median age of 65 years at diagnosis of MCL, half of the patients are not eligible for the β€�standardβ€� therapy with autologous transplantation. However, even with a less intensive treatment the outcome of the fit elderly patient has improved by incorporating rituximab and maintenance therapy.
Studies investigating minimal residual disease have shown that those patients achieving a molecular complete remission after therapy have a low risk of early progression, and in general have a long event-free survival. It is therefore important to try to obtain a complete remission, also for elderly patients.30
The backbone of therapy is R-CHOP. This regimen is repeated every 3 weeks, up to eight courses. The result is generally a reduction of lymphadenopathy and other symptoms. Overall responses (complete and partial remissions combined) of approximately 85% can be obtained. A complete remission (CR), no signs of disease left on computed tomography scan and other restaging procedures, is achieved in 30%β€“40% of patients.18,31 Relapse or progression is common after 2β€“3 years.18
The European MCL Network designed a study that aimed to improve the results of induction therapy, and to prolong the duration of remission. In this randomized, multicenter study, the standard R-CHOP, eight cycles, was compared with rituximab, the purine analog fludarabine, and cyclophosphamide (R-FC), every 4 weeks, a total of six cycles. The responding patients were randomized between maintenance therapy with interferon-alpha or rituximab. This maintenance treatment was planned to continue until progression.31 In almost 7 years, 560 patients from eight countries were randomized. The median age was 70 years. The results were unexpected. The new induction regimen R-FC did not improve the outcome; in both treatment arms the response rate (partial response and complete response) was not statistically different: after R-CHOP 86%, after R-FC 78%. The CR rate was 34% and 40% respectively, also not statistically different. The OS in the R-CHOP-treated patients was better than in the R-FC-treated patients, the survival rate after 4 years being 62% versus 47%. The toxicity of R-FC was more severe, especially hematologic toxicity, and infections were observed more frequently.
The outcome of the maintenance treatment was very much in favor of rituximab. After 4 years, 58% of the patients had not shown progression or relapse, compared with 29% of the patients that started interferon maintenance. This resulted in a 4-year OS in the patients treated with R-CHOP and rituximab maintenance of almost 85%. Eight cycles of R-CHOP followed by rituximab maintenance therefore now is considered the standard treatment for elderly patients with MCL, until a new study will hopefully show further improved outcome data.
An alternative alkylating agent is bendamustine. This agent has been used for the treatment of indolent lymphomas and MCL in Germany for more than 20 years, but was only approved in Europe and US a few years ago. In a recently randomized study in patients with indolent lymphoma or MCL, R-CHOP has been compared with R-bendamustine.32 The study was designed as a noninferiority trial. The toxicity of R-bendamustine was lower, except for skin rash. Erythema or allergic reactions of the skin were observed in 31% of the patients, compared with 15% after R-CHOP. Ninety-four patients in this study (18%), with a median age of 70 years, were diagnosed with a MCL. The median PFS of the MCL patients was 35 months with R-bendamustine, compared with 22 months after R-CHOP. No difference in OS has been observed, however. A second study, not yet published, for indolent lymphomas including MCL, has been initiated in the USA. In this study, R-bendamustine is being compared with R-CHOP or R-CVP (rituximab with cyclophosphamide, vincristine, and prednisone).
