<sections.6>
Treatment of the frail elderly patient
or the frail elderly patient, therapy should aim to reduce symptoms and maintain quality of life. sually, the very elderly patient, or the patient with severe comorbidity, cannot be treated with -.  less intensive regimen should be selected to reduce symptoms. n some patients, - might be feasible: doxorubicin is responsible for many of the side effects of -, ie, nausea and vomiting and neutropenia. here is no risk to further reduction of cardiac function without the administration of doxorubicin.
n alternative for the frail elderly is oral chlorambucil that might be combined with rituximab. his is a well-tolerated regimen in most patients.33
he results of monotherapy rituximab are not very impressive. n overall response rate of 27% has been observed, with an event-free survival of 6 months, which is less than can be obtained in follicular lymphoma. onger treatment did not significantly improve the outcome.34
inally, in the case of localized symptomatic lymphadenopathy, local control can be obtained by radiotherapy.35Treatment of the frail elderly patient
For the frail elderly patient, therapy should aim to reduce symptoms and maintain quality of life. Usually, the very elderly patient, or the patient with severe comorbidity, cannot be treated with R-CHOP. A less intensive regimen should be selected to reduce symptoms. In some patients, R-CVP might be feasible: doxorubicin is responsible for many of the side effects of R-CHOP, ie, nausea and vomiting and neutropenia. There is no risk to further reduction of cardiac function without the administration of doxorubicin.
An alternative for the frail elderly is oral chlorambucil that might be combined with rituximab. This is a well-tolerated regimen in most patients.33
The results of monotherapy rituximab are not very impressive. An overall response rate of 27% has been observed, with an event-free survival of 6 months, which is less than can be obtained in follicular lymphoma. Longer treatment did not significantly improve the outcome.34
Finally, in the case of localized symptomatic lymphadenopathy, local control can be obtained by radiotherapy.35
