<sections.7>
Therapy of relapsed or progressive elderly  patients
lthough the results of upfront treatment have improved, finally patients will show relapse or progressive disease. here is no standard therapy for relapse or progression. everal options are mentioned as follows (overview in able 2). ost of the studies with relapsed/refractory patients are not specifically designed for elderly patients, but most of them have included elderly patients as well, as is reflected in the median age.
ituximab/bendamustine is an active regimen for , and can be used in the relapsed setting.36 etreatment with bendamustine is possible, although no details are known about its effectiveness in .37 ombination therapy with mitoxantrone may be an option.38
ludarabine/cyclophosphamide () is also active in relapsed .39 he combination rituximab, fludarabine, cyclophosphamide, and mitoxantrone (-) can result in a response rate of 58%β€“79%.40,41 owever, - is not suitable for patients who have received  because of the cumulative cardiac anthracycline toxicity. aintenance rituximab does not significantly improve the response duration but increases the number of patients with remissions beyond 2 years.41
he major side effect of fludarabine-containing regimens is hematologic toxicity. n the upfront setting, - was inferior compared with -, mainly caused by increased toxicity.31 owever, fludarabine is an effective drug in the treatment of , and it might be considered in the relapse setting. t is important to select the fitter patients for this treatment.
ost elderly patients have not received high dose cytarabine in first-line treatment. here are some data that show a reduced dose cytarabine is also effective. his might be considered in the relapse setting. n a hase  study in elderly patients, the combination rituximab, bendamustine, and cytarabine (-) has been explored. wenty patients had been previously treated. he - regimen was effective, but had a high rate of myelosuppression.  new study with a lower dose of cytarabine has been started.42
onotherapy with the purine nucleoside analog cladribine has shown some activity in relapsed , with relatively low toxicity.43
n the , the proteasome inhibitor bortezomib has been approved for the treatment of relapsed or progressive . ctivation of the nuclear factor kappa  (-) is an important result of the activated proliferation pathway in . ortezomib has been shown to inhibit - activation. onotherapy with bortezomib can result in a response rate of 30%β€“45%, but a median  of only 6 months.44,45 he major side effect of bortezomib is neuropathy, either a sensory neuropathy or neuropathic pain. ith the recently introduced use of subcutaneous instead of intravenous administration, the risk of neuropathy has decreased.46 ombination of bortezomib with cytarabine has also been explored, and seems feasible with a dose adjustment for elderly patients.47
n urope, temsirolimus, an m. TOR (mammalian target of rapamycin) kinase inhibitor, is approved for relapsed MCL. In the PI3K/AKT pathway, which plays a major role in the proliferation of MCL, mTOR is one of the regulatory proteins. So it seemed attractive to investigate this drug in relapsed MCL. In relapsed/refractory MCL, single-agent temsirolimus achieves a response in 40% of patients, with only 3% complete remissions, however. The median duration of response is only 6 months.48,49 In a randomized Phase III study, temsirolimus has been compared to single-agent physicianβ€™s choice therapy. Again, in a heavily pretreated group of patients, with a median of three previous lines of therapy (range 2β€“7), the PFS with temsirolimus monotherapy was only 5 months. The major toxicities of temsirolimus are thrombocytopenia, diarrhea, and asthenia.50
Lenalidomide, an immunomodulatory drug that is active in several B-cell malignancies, has been studied in relapsed MCL. The reported response rates are 42%β€“55%, with a PFS of 6 months.51,52 To date, no randomized studies with lenalidomide have been performed in MCL, but these results are promising.
In a selective group of younger patients, an allogeneic transplantation may be considered after successful reinduction therapy. An allogeneic transplantation is the only curative option, but the treatment-related mortality is considerable, up to 30%. Acute and chronic graft versus host disease is common, and has a major impact on quality of life.53
In elderly patients an allogeneic transplantation will rarely be the choice of therapy.
In a palliative setting, radiotherapy is an attractive option to treat symptoms resulting from enlarged lymph nodes. MCL is radiosensitive, so radiotherapy is useful to achieve local control.35
